The third day of the Jaipur Literature Festival began with understanding, re-visiting and examining the relevance of the Constitution. In the session, Of the people, by the people: The Indian Constitution, former Election Commissioner of India, Navin Chawla, legal scholar and author of The Indian Constitution, Madhav Khosla, and politician Margaret Alva were in conversation with author and Supreme Court lawyer Saif Mahmood. As expected, the recent anti-CAA protests overshadowed the conversation.

Emphasising on the need to make the text work, Khosla asserts that it is on us to see that it does. â€œWhether or not the Constitution works or not has to depend on some external commitment to making it work. Imagine, if you have a refrigerator and if you are not plugging in, how will it work? I think people at the time understood this. This was the reason why Nehru wrote letters to chief ministers every two weeks. He was basically saying that democracy will go as fast as the British government went.â€

